            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is a control premium?</h2>
              <p>
                In mergers and acquisitions, a
                <strong>control premium</strong> is the percentage amount an
                acquirer pays <em>above</em> the current market or minority
                equity value to obtain a controlling interest in a company. It
                reflects the value of control rights, such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Setting corporate strategy and business plan</li>
                <li>Appointing and removing management and board members</li>
                <li>
                  Deciding on dividends, share buybacks, and capital structure
                </li>
                <li>Approving acquisitions, divestitures, and asset sales</li>
                <li>Accessing and realizing synergies with the acquirer</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Public M&amp;A studies often report control premiums in the
                <strong>20–40%</strong> range over unaffected share prices, but
                actual premiums vary widely by sector, governance quality, and
                deal-specific synergies.
              </p>

              <h2>Control premium formulas</h2>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">1. Per-share control premium</p>
                <p>
                  Let \( P_m \) be the unaffected market (minority) price per
                  share and \( P_c \) the deal (control) price per share.
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{Control Premium} = \frac{P_c}{P_m} - 1 \]</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  2. Equity value control premium
                </p>
                <p>
                  Let \( V_m \) be the minority equity value (pre-deal) and \(
                  V_c \) the equity value implied by the deal.
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{Control Premium} = \frac{V_c}{V_m} - 1 \]</p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  3. Discount for lack of control (DLOC)
                </p>
                <p>
                  If a control premium \( CP \) is known, the implied
                  <strong>discount for lack of control</strong> is:
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{DLOC} = 1 - \frac{1}{1 + CP} \]</p>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">
                  Example: If \( CP = 30\% \), then \( \text{DLOC} = 1 - 1 /
                  1.30 \approx 23.1\% \).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use the Control Premium Calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter unaffected market price per share.</strong>
                  Use the pre-announcement trading price, or a volume-weighted
                  average price (VWAP) over a period before rumors or leaks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the deal price per share.</strong>
                  This is the offer price the acquirer is paying for the
                  controlling stake (cash, stock-equivalent, or blended).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optionally enter shares outstanding.</strong>
                  If you provide total shares, the tool will compute total
                  equity values at both market and deal prices.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Optionally enter equity values directly.</strong>
                  If you only know total equity values (e.g., from a valuation
                  report), enter minority and control equity values to compute a
                  control premium on that basis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Review the outputs.</strong>
                  The calculator shows:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Control premium (per share and, if available, on equity
                      value)
                    </li>
                    <li>Implied minority and control prices per share</li>
                    <li>Discount for lack of control (DLOC)</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Interpreting the results</h2>
              <h3>1. Control premium</h3>
              <p>
                A higher control premium suggests that the acquirer expects
                significant <strong>synergies</strong> or believes the target is
                <strong>undervalued</strong> as a minority trading stock. It may
                also reflect competitive bidding, strong bargaining power of the
                seller, or a scarcity of comparable assets.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Discount for lack of control (DLOC)</h3>
              <p>
                The DLOC translates a control-level value back to a
                minority-level value. For example, if a private company is
                valued on a controlling basis using a DCF, you might apply a
                DLOC to estimate the value of a minority, non-controlling stake.
              </p>

              <h3>3. When <em>not</em> to apply a control premium</h3>
              <p>
                A common pitfall is <strong>double counting control</strong>. If
                your valuation method already assumes control (e.g., a DCF with
                optimized capital structure and normalized operations), you are
                already at a control level of value and should
                <strong>not</strong> add a separate control premium.
              </p>
              <p>
                Conversely, if you are using
                <strong>trading multiples</strong> from minority market prices
                and want a control-level conclusion, it may be appropriate to
                adjust for control, depending on the standard of value (fair
                market value vs. investment value) and jurisdictional practice.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical example</h2>
              <p>Assume the following:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Unaffected market price per share \( P_m = \$20.00 \)</li>
                <li>Deal price per share \( P_c = \$26.00 \)</li>
                <li>Shares outstanding = 50 million</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Control premium = \( 26 / 20 - 1 = 30\% \)</li>
                <li>
                  Minority equity value = \( 20 \times 50\text{m} =
                  \$1.0\text{bn} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Control equity value = \( 26 \times 50\text{m} =
                  \$1.3\text{bn} \)
                </li>
                <li>DLOC = \( 1 - 1 / 1.30 \approx 23.1\% \)</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and best practices</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use unaffected prices.</strong> Always base control
                  premiums on prices before deal rumors or leaks to avoid
                  overstating the premium.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Segment by sector and region.</strong> Control
                  premiums differ by industry, country, and market cycle;
                  empirical studies should be filtered accordingly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Align with the standard of value.</strong> Ensure
                  consistency between your valuation approach (control vs.
                  minority) and any adjustments for control or lack of control.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider synergies separately.</strong> Synergy value
                  may belong to the buyer, seller, or both; some practitioners
                  treat it separately from pure control rights.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions about control premiums</h2>

              <h3>What is a control premium?</h3>
              <p>
                A control premium is the percentage amount an acquirer is
                willing to pay above the current market or minority equity value
                to obtain a controlling interest in a company. It reflects the
                value of being able to direct the company’s strategy,
                operations, and financial policies.
              </p>

              <h3>How do you calculate control premium?</h3>
              <p>The most common method is:</p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{Control Premium} = \frac{\text{Deal Price per
                Share}}{\text{Unaffected Market Price per Share}} - 1 \]
              </p>
              <p>
                You can apply the same formula using total equity values instead
                of per-share prices.
              </p>

              <h3>What is the discount for lack of control (DLOC)?</h3>
              <p>
                The DLOC is the percentage reduction applied to a control-level
                value to reflect the lower value of a minority, non-controlling
                interest. If you know the control premium \( CP \), the implied
                DLOC is:
              </p>
              <p>\[ \text{DLOC} = 1 - \frac{1}{1 + CP} \]</p>

              <h3>What is a typical range for control premiums?</h3>
              <p>
                Studies of public company takeovers often show median control
                premiums in the 20–40% range over unaffected market prices.
                However, premiums can be much lower or higher depending on:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Expected synergies and cost savings</li>
                <li>Competition among bidders</li>
                <li>
                  Quality of corporate governance and shareholder protections
                </li>
                <li>
                  Target’s performance, growth prospects, and sector dynamics
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Should I always apply a control premium in valuation?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Whether you apply a control premium depends on the
                <strong>level of value</strong> implied by your valuation
                method:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If your DCF or transaction multiples already assume control
                  (e.g., optimized capital structure, removal of inefficient
                  management), you are likely at a control level of value and
                  should <strong>not</strong> add a separate control premium.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you are using trading multiples from minority market prices
                  and need a control-level conclusion, a control adjustment may
                  be appropriate, subject to professional judgment and local
                  valuation standards.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
